# Introduction

Machine learning models are among the most valuable assets within an Artificial Intelligence (AI) ecosystem. Organizations invest significant time, expertise, computing resources, and data to develop models that support business operations, automate decision-making, and provide competitive advantages.

Unlike traditional software, AI models continuously rely on data, parameters, and algorithms to generate predictions. If an AI model is compromised, attackers may manipulate its behavior, steal proprietary intellectual property, expose sensitive information, or reduce the reliability of AI-driven decisions.

Model security focuses on protecting machine learning models from unauthorized access, modification, theft, and misuse throughout their lifecycle. It combines cybersecurity controls, governance processes, operational procedures, and continuous monitoring to ensure AI models remain trustworthy, reliable, and resilient.

Within an Artificial Intelligence Management System (AIMS), model security is an essential component of AI governance because it protects the integrity and availability of AI capabilities that support business operations.

---

# What is Model Security?

Model security refers to the collection of technical, operational, and governance controls that protect machine learning models throughout their lifecycle.

Model security aims to ensure that AI models remain:

- Accurate.
- Reliable.
- Confidential.
- Available.
- Resistant to manipulation.
- Properly governed.

Effective model security protects not only the AI model itself but also the supporting components that enable the model to operate securely.

---

# Why Model Security Matters

Machine learning models often represent valuable business assets and may process sensitive or regulated information.

Without appropriate model security controls, organizations may experience:

| Risk Area | Example |
|------|------|
| Intellectual Property Risk | Proprietary AI models are stolen |
| Operational Risk | Manipulated models produce inaccurate predictions |
| Security Risk | Unauthorized users modify AI models |
| Compliance Risk | AI models violate governance or regulatory requirements |
